Linear models with factors

Read the chapter 14-16

Predictors that are qualitative in nature, for example, eye color, are sometimes described as categorical or called factors. We wish to incorporate these predictors into the regression analysis.

1 A two level factor

The dataset sexab for this example come from a study of the effects of childhood sexual abuse on adult females. See the data description in R.

t.test(ptsd ~ csa, sexab, var.equal=TRUE)

We find the difference is significant.

Our strategy is to incorporate qualitative predictors within the linear regression framework. We can do this using a dummy variable. For a categorical predictor (or factor) with two levels, we define a dummy variable as

\[d = I(CSA ~ is ~ reported)\]

d <- ifelse(sexab$csa == "Abused",1,0)
lmod <- lm(ptsd ~ d, sexab)
sumary(lmod)

The estiamted model is

\[\widehat{PTSD} = 4.70 + 7.25*d\]

What does the estimated coefficients mean? The intercept (4.70) is the mean PTSD for non-abused group (\(d=0\)). The slope (7.25) means the difference on the mean PTSD between groups (abused vs non-abused). And, the above result tells us that the slope is significant, which means that there is a significant difference betweeb groups. This result is consistent with that of T-test. Moreover, we can see that the observed test statistic (8.9387) coincide.

Note] We need the equal variances assumption for our regression model to be valid. And, observe that we performed the T-test under the equal variances assumption as well.

In fact, we dont need to introduce the dummy variable in this example since in many cases it is automatically done by R.

lmod <- lm(ptsd ~ csa, sexab)
sumary(lmod)
##              Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  11.94109    0.51767 23.0670 < 2.2e-16
## csaNotAbused -7.24522    0.81055 -8.9387 2.172e-13
## 
## n = 76, p = 2, Residual SE = 3.47264, R-Squared = 0.52
class(sexab$csa)
## [1] "factor"

Note here that the sign of the estimated slope is reversed. This is because, in R, the reference level (0 level) is alphabetically determined. If one want to change it manullay, do as

sexab$csa <- relevel(sexab$csa, ref="NotAbused")
lmod <- lm(ptsd ~ csa, sexab)
sumary(lmod)
##             Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  4.69587    0.62370  7.5290 1.003e-10
## csaAbused    7.24522    0.81055  8.9387 2.172e-13
## 
## n = 76, p = 2, Residual SE = 3.47264, R-Squared = 0.52

Note that they give essentially the same information.

2 Factors and Quantitative Predictors

Now we add CPA (quantitative) variable into the model. Therefore, we now have two predictors. This may give some adjustment into the model since CPA(\(x\)) may also affect PTSD(\(y\)) as well as CSA(\(d\)). We are going to try two models

  1. Regression lines for each group with the same slope: \(y=\beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \beta_2 d + \epsilon\)
  2. Regression lines for each group with the different slopes: \(y=\beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \beta_2 d + \beta_3 xd + \epsilon\)

We call \(\beta_3\) a interaction effect since this produces a different slopes for different levels of \(d\).

lmod4 <- lm(ptsd ~ cpa+csa+cpa:csa,sexab)
#lmod4 <- lm(ptsd ~ cpa*csa,sexab)   #   the same as above
sumary(lmod4)
##               Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)    3.69591    0.71066  5.2007 1.790e-06
## cpa            0.76400    0.30383  2.5146   0.01415
## csaAbused      6.86121    1.07475  6.3840 1.479e-08
## cpa:csaAbused -0.31396    0.36848 -0.8520   0.39702
## 
## n = 76, p = 4, Residual SE = 3.27931, R-Squared = 0.58
head(model.matrix(lmod4))
##   (Intercept)      cpa csaAbused cpa:csaAbused
## 1           1  2.04786         1       2.04786
## 2           1  0.83895         1       0.83895
## 3           1 -0.24139         1      -0.24139
## 4           1 -1.11461         1      -1.11461
## 5           1  2.01468         1       2.01468
## 6           1  6.71131         1       6.71131
plot(ptsd ~ cpa, sexab, pch=as.numeric(csa))
abline(3.96, 0.764)
abline(3.96+6.86, 0.764-0.314,lty=2)

The model can be simplified because the interaction term is not significant. We reduce to this model:

lmod3 <- lm(ptsd ~ cpa+csa,sexab)
sumary(lmod3)
##             Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  3.97528    0.62931  6.3169 1.871e-08
## cpa          0.55055    0.17158  3.2086  0.001982
## csaAbused    6.27275    0.82191  7.6320 6.907e-11
## 
## n = 76, p = 3, Residual SE = 3.27314, R-Squared = 0.58
plot(ptsd ~ cpa, sexab, pch=as.numeric(csa))
abline(3.98, 0.551)
abline(3.98+6.27, 0.551, lty=2)
ma = mean(sexab$ptsd[sexab$csa == "Abused"])
mna = mean(sexab$ptsd[sexab$csa != "Abused"])
abline(h=ma,col=2)
abline(h=mna,col=2, lty=2)

Now the two linear lines are parallel. Note that the slope of both lines is 0.551, but the Abused line is 6.273 higher than the NonAbused. From the one predictor model earlier, the unadjusted estimated effect of childhood sexual abuse is 7.245. So after adjusting for the effect of childhood physical abuse, our estimate of the effect of childhood sexual abuse on PTSD is mildly reduced. This can be viewed in the above plot (red lines).

A homeowner in England recorded his weekly natural gas consumption, in thousands of cubic feet, during two winter heating seasons. For the second season, cavity wall insulation had been installed. The homeowner also recorded the average weekly temperature in degrees Celsius because this would also affect gas consumption. The data may be found in the MASS package.

data(whiteside,package="MASS")
require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
ggplot(aes(x=Temp,y=Gas),data=whiteside)+geom_point()+facet_grid(~ Insul)+geom_smooth(method="lm")

We can see that less gas is used after the insulation is installed but the difference varies by temperature.

3 Factors With More Than Two Levels

Suppose we have a factor with 3 levels (A,B,C). Then, we need 2 dummy variables to include the factor into the model properly.

\[d_1=I(B),~d_2 = I(C).\]

If the level is A, \(d_1=0,d_2=0\). If the level is B, \(d_1=1, d_2=0\). If it is C, \(d_1=0,d_2=1\). Of course, different kinds of definitions are possible. Generally, we need \(f-1\) dummy variabels with a \(f\) levels factor variable.

We demonstrate the use of multilevel factors with a study on the sexual activity and the life span of male fruitflies by Partridge and Farquhar (1981): 125 fruitflies were divided randomly into five groups of 25 each. The response was the longevity of the fruitfly in days. One group was kept solitary, while another was kept individually with a virgin female each day. Another group was given eight virgin females per day. As an additional control, the fourth and fifth groups were kept with one or eight pregnant females per day. Pregnant fruitflies will not mate. The thorax length of each male was measured as this was known to affect longevity. The five groups are labeled isolated, low, high, one and many respectively.

data(fruitfly,package="faraway")
plot(longevity ~ thorax, fruitfly, pch=unclass(activity))
legend(0.63,100,levels(fruitfly$activity),pch=1:5)

require(ggplot2)
ggplot(aes(x=thorax,y=longevity),data=fruitfly) + geom_point() + facet_wrap( ~ activity)

lmod <- lm(longevity ~ thorax*activity, fruitfly)
sumary(lmod)

4 ALternative codings

Consider a four-level factor that will be coded using three dummy variables. This contrast matrix describes the coding, where the columns represent the dummy variables and the rows represent the levels:

Lets see by 4 levels example.

contr.treatment(4)  # Treatment coding (default in R)
##   2 3 4
## 1 0 0 0
## 2 1 0 0
## 3 0 1 0
## 4 0 0 1
contr.helmert(4)    # Helmert coding
##   [,1] [,2] [,3]
## 1   -1   -1   -1
## 2    1   -1   -1
## 3    0    2   -1
## 4    0    0    3
contr.sum(4)        # sum coding (intercept becomes the mean response)
##   [,1] [,2] [,3]
## 1    1    0    0
## 2    0    1    0
## 3    0    0    1
## 4   -1   -1   -1
contrasts(sexab$csa) <- contr.sum(2)
sumary(lm(ptsd ~ csa, sexab))
##             Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  8.31848    0.40527 20.5256 < 2.2e-16
## csa1        -3.62261    0.40527 -8.9387 2.172e-13
## 
## n = 76, p = 2, Residual SE = 3.47264, R-Squared = 0.52

The mean response is 8.32. And, the effect is \(8.32 \pm 3.62\).
